label chapter4:

    # [Scene: Marsh Planting Sites | Night]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Urgent footsteps on wood, the rasp of coir, a low tide rumble like a far-off train]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: High-tempo percussion with a hopeful brass thread]
    "You said it in the council room and then walked out: mobilize tonight. The words are still warm in your mouth as you step off the pier and into the work—no ceremony, just motion. Volunteers fold"
    "and unfold around you like sails catching a sudden wind. Lina hauls a battered tote of seedlings, hoodie streaked with paint; her breath fogs in the beam of her headlamp. Aiden Reyes is already there, waxed"
    "jacket shining, passing out lengths of rope with the same quick, careful efficiency he gives to a net. Priya Anand's clipboard glows with margins of grant notes; even in the dark she looks like a promise."
    "You can feel the tide’s timing in your chest—an internal metronome. Every action is aligned to that beat: hammer, stitch, plant, step back. Your multi-tool clicks when you drive a stake; the sound is a staccato"
    "that keeps everyone moving. The marsh smells like wet earth and salt and old wood—close and intimate. You start humming an old dock song under your breath, low enough not to be a directive but loud"
    "enough to give rhythm to tired hands. The song threads through the swearing and the laughter, and people answer it with small, steady noises—a joined cadence forming out of obligation and hope."
    show lina_kwon at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_kwon "We brought extra plugs. Mateo said bring gloves for everyone—said his hands weren't up for planting, but he couldn't stay away."
    show maya_kwon at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "Perfect. Hand me a coil of coir—I'll start the southern wicket."

    lina_kwon "You sure we can finish the channel before the high?"

    maya_kwon "We have to. Even if it’s rude to the tide."
    "Lina laughs, breathless, and digs in. You pass her the coil. Her hands are clumsy in the dark, but sure. You show her how to loop the mini-berm ties; she gets it on the second try."
    "There’s a back-and-forth that becomes its own instruction manual: you, a patient teacher; she, the town's impatience turned practical."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Phone ping—short and clinical]
    hide lina_kwon
    hide maya_kwon

    scene bg ch4_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Message tone is a flat, corporate chirp]

    "You glance. Dr. Elara Voss's message is terse" "Uncoordinated intervention risks. Please halt pending review."

    menu:
        "Reply: 'We’ll coordinate with you tomorrow'":
            "Your thumb hovers. You draft a short line of professional assurance, then stop. For now, the marsh needs you more than the argument does."
        "Ignore it and keep working":
            "You tuck the phone away and feel the tension leave your jaw. The message exists in the world; it doesn't yet have your consent to shape tonight."

    # --- merge ---
    "The team continues their work, guided by tide and momentum."
    "You push on. Priya Anand materializes at your elbow with a muddy grin and a clipboard that’s somehow more luminous than the headlamps. She waves a printed grant checklist like a talisman."
    show priya_anand at left:
        zoom 0.7

    priya_anand "Emergency funds cleared for pilot plots. The paperwork is a mess, but it's green-lit. You did good getting people here."
    show maya_kwon at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "We got the hands—now we make sure the work is solid enough they can sign off in the morning."

    priya_anand "Exactly. Show momentum, show method. Do both, sleep later."
    "You nod. Priya's beam of certainty is a lantern in the bureaucratic fog. Her eyes flick to the stakes, the coir logs, the pattern of channels you're unwrapping in the mud. You can see in her"
    "face the calculations turning into moral weight: grants want measurable metrics; the marsh wants rooted life. Both can be true tonight, you tell yourself."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Old Man Reyes's boots on wood, slower, measured]
    hide priya_anand
    hide maya_kwon

    scene bg ch4_453e40_3 at full_bg

    "Mateo Reyes" "You young ones never did wait for the moon. You rush like tidewater—quick and hungry."
    show maya_kwon at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "We rush to beat the high, Mateo. We can't afford to miss the window."

    "Mateo Reyes" "Window? I remember a tide path my father used when the channel was twice the width. You lot are right to be stubborn. Just don't forget the old lines; they taught the fish where to go."
    "He points with a finger that still remembers rope. You lean in; his weathered hands scoop mud like a map. He tells a short, sharp story about a vanished creek bed and how the eels used"
    "to slip through on spring flood. At the end, he presses the thermos into Lina's hands."

    "Mateo Reyes" "Drink. You'll need it."
    "Aiden Reyes works beside you until his gloves are salt-dark and slick. You pass him a bundle of eelgrass frames; he takes them with an easy joke to hide his concentration, knotting the netting around a wooden armature as if tying the future into place."
    show aiden_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aiden_reyes "You humming again? I can't decide if that's comforting or an old curse."

    maya_kwon "Depends who listens. Keeps the rhythm."

    aiden_reyes "Cool—keep humming. It helps me not think about how my hands might collapse if I stop moving."
    "His shoulder brushes yours when he hands you another stake. The contact is brief, almost accidental, but it lands like a small anchor. For a heartbeat your chest steadies; the tide in you finds a dock."
    "You push that private warmth back into your throat and translate it into motion—hammer, knot, plant."

    menu:
        "Sing the dock song louder to keep morale up":
            "You let the chorus swell. Voices pick it up—rough, beautiful, determined. The work gains speed; people follow the cue like migrating birds."
        "Keep humming quietly so the team can focus":
            "You fold the song into your breath. The group's focus narrows; the hands move with precise coordination, like a practiced crew."

    # --- merge ---
    "The planting continues with either increased momentum or tightened precision."
    "The pilot's methods are primitive—coir logs pinned into place, channels pried gently open, plugs of Spartina snugged into spooned holes. You sink eelgrass frames in shallow pools where the light catches and the water accepts them"
    "like a slow promise. The physicality is honest: rubbed knuckles, boots sucked to gravel, jackets smeared with the town’s ink. People shout coordinates in clipped tones. Someone drops a hammer. Someone laughs too loud. The tempo"
    "climbs."
    "The sky lightens a single shade. Dawn is a rumor on the horizon, silvering the reeds. You think of every lecture you ever gave, every grant table you sat behind; nothing taught you what you learn"
    "with mud under your nails and a community's hands at your elbow. This is doing—the kind of doing that rewires fear into forward motion."
    show priya_anand at center:
        zoom 0.7

    priya_anand "We should mark the plots for monitoring. Photo logs, GPS points—I'll start the forms now."

    maya_kwon "Do it. Mateo, can you show Lina that tide notch so she knows how far to expect the flood?"

    "Mateo Reyes" "Aye. Come on then, girl."
    "Lina follows, eyes bright despite the cold; she takes notes as if they are treasures. You steal a second to look across the site: rows of planted plugs, new channels that will slow water rather than"
    "hurl it; people tied together by rope and purpose. Your chest rings with an urgency that is almost joy. This is the night you stop waiting."
    "The sky becomes a wash of pale and the boardwalks start to glisten. Someone atop a distant roof switches on a kettle; the smell of coffee floats weak and golden. A few early risers from adjacent"
    "houses step onto their porches to watch. They stand like sentries, silent and careful, as if the sight of the town moving itself is too fragile to applaud."
    "A message pings again—another terse note from wary city planners—but it is softened by a new one: Priya Anand's shout, half-triumph, half-practicality."

    priya_anand "Photos taken. GPS logged. Volunteers signed up for morning monitoring. Mateo—people want to learn how to maintain this."

    "Mateo Reyes" "Tell them I charge in stories and thermos."
    "Aiden Reyes pauses mid-knot and looks at you, the tide-light framing his face. For all the talk of techniques and permits, there is a human ledger being written here—one you feel in your ribs. He speaks slowly."

    aiden_reyes "We did it. We actually did it tonight. They'll see this and want in."

    maya_kwon "Tonight proves we can move. It proves momentum matters."

    aiden_reyes "And it proves you're not just talk. That's important—around here, talk's cheap."
    "You let his praise sit. It is not flattery; it is observed truth. You catch the glint of townlight in the mud and in the eyes of those who came out to watch. Momentum, you realize, is contagious."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A rising chorus of distant voices—greetings, the shuffling of more feet]
    hide maya_kwon
    hide aiden_reyes
    hide priya_anand

    scene bg ch4_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Crescendo—brass and strings meet drums; triumphant without hubris]
    "By dawn the beds hold. The newly opened channels shine with thin, quick water. Boards on the walkways throw back the first clean light. The town is awake, and it watches, breath held and then released"
    "in a low, rolling approval that is almost a sound. People nod at one another across the marsh like old friends signing a pact."
    "You stand in the center of it, breathing the cool, salt-laden air. Your notebook is heavy in your pocket; your hands are raw and blessed with work. The pilot is primitive, hopeful, and visible. Tonight, you"
    "did more than plant—it is the night you showed a model could move from map to mud. From plan to people."

    scene bg ch4_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The thermos hissing again as someone pours a share; a new day begins]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A soft return to the dock-song motif, now broader and communal]
    "You feel the momentum like a tide under your feet. It isn't guaranteed. There will be meetings, arguments, and engineers with tidy lines. But for the moment, the town has chosen action. The work hums through your bones."
    # [Page-Turn Moment]
    "You let the view settle in—mud on knuckles, the smell of fresh-cut cordgrass, Priya Anand's bright grin, Mateo Reyes's quiet story, Aiden Reyes's steadying presence. A new band of neighbors gathers along the boardwalks, signing up"
    "in low voices to watch plots and feed logs. The world is narrow and vast at once: narrow because this pilot is a single night of labor; vast because this night could be the seed of"
    "every shore you will ever defend. You tuck the multi-tool back into your belt, feel the pulse of the town in your palms, and hear the next step clicking into place: more hands tomorrow, more beds"
    "to plant, a surge that will not be stopped by a single message. There is a long road ahead, but you have taken the first run."

    scene bg ch4_453e40_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    jump chapter5
    return
